                     The white and yellow, or redlike wines which are of a thin and subtile substance,
together with the claret, weake, waterie, rawe, and greenish, being of a cold and
moist temperature, (such as are very vsuall and common in the grounds about Paris)
do nourish the bodie very little, and are harder to be digested, than those which
will beare but a little water, but they coole and moisten more than the 
