the drie, rough, stiffe, and grauellie grounds, if they be not mingled with moisture.
The auncient Woodwards vsed to plant them most in hedge-rowes, and on
the tops of great bankes or ditches, where they might haue drie standing, yet be continually
fed at the root with a little moisture: vvhich sure was a very good and husbandly
manner of planting the Ash, neither shall you at any time see it prosper better,
than when it is planted in such places. It is naturally of it selfe 
